ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The mobile app doesn\'t actually import the generated auth models any
where in its own code. The `flutter analyze` failure is because the generated co
de is inside `apps/mobile/lib/` and the analyzer scans all files under `lib/`. T
he generated code has broken imports within itself.\n\nSo the fix needs to make 
the generated code valid from the analyzer\'s perspective.\n\nLet me think about
the simplest fix:\n1. Add the path dependency to `apps/mobile/pubspec.yaml`\n2. 
The `.g.dart` files will still be missing\n\nBut wait - `flutter analyze` doesn\
't necessarily fail on missing `part` files if those files are themselves in a p
ackage that\'s not being analyzed as part of the main app. No, that\'s not right
. `flutter analyze` analyzes ALL Dart files under `lib/`, including those in sub
directories. So it WILL analyze the generated auth package files.\n\nActually, w
hen a package is added as a path dependency, `flutter analyze` on the main app m
ight not deeply analyze the dependency\'s internal files unless they\'re importe
d. But `flutter analyze` does analyze all files in the current package\'s `lib/`
directory. Since the generated auth code is INSIDE `apps/mobile/lib/models/gener
ated/auth/lib/`, it IS part of the mobile app\'s package, not a separate package
from the analyzer\'s perspective.\n\nWait, no. The generated auth code has its o
wn `pubspec.yaml` at `apps/mobile/lib/models/generated/auth/pubspec.yaml`, but i
t\'s inside the `lib/` directory of the mobile app. This is a very unusual layou
t. The Dart analyzer might see the `pubspec.yaml` and treat it as a separate pac
kage, OR it might just treat all `.dart` files under `apps/mobile/lib/` as part 
of `social_world_mobile` package.\n\nActually, in Dart/Flutter, a `pubspec.yaml`
defines a package boundary. If there\'s a `pubspec.yaml` inside `lib/models/gene
rated/auth/`, then that directory IS a separate package. The analyzer should res
pect that boundary. But `flutter analyze` in `apps/mobile/` analyzes the `social
_world_mobile` package and its dependencies. Files in `lib/models/generated/auth
/lib/` are NOT part of `social_world_mobile`\'s `lib/` from the package perspect
ive because there\'s an inner `pubspec.yaml`.\n\nWait, actually that\'s not quit
e right either. The presence of a nested `pubspec.yaml` inside `lib/` doesn\'t a
utomatically exclude those files from the outer package\'s analysis. The Dart an
alyzer might still see `.dart` files there and try to analyze them, but they\'ll
be analyzed as part of the outer package unless the analyzer understands the nes
ted package boundary.\n\nHmm, looking at the CI output, the errors are:\n- `lib/
models/generated/auth/lib/social_world_auth_models.dart:5:8 • uri_does_not_exist
`\n- `lib/models/generated/auth/lib/src/api.dart:7:8 • uri_does_not_exist`\n\nTh
ese paths suggest the analyzer IS looking at these files. So they are being anal
yzed.\n\nIf I add the path dependency to `apps/mobile/pubspec.yaml`, then the ne
sted package `social_world_auth_models` becomes a proper dependency. But the fil
es in `lib/models/generated/auth/lib/` might STILL be analyzed as part of the mo
bile app because of their physical location.\n\nActually, the correct approach m
ight be to move the generated package OUTSIDE of `apps/mobile/lib/`. Generated p
ackages should typically be in a separate directory, like `packages/mobile_model
s/` or `apps/mobile/packages/`.\n\nBut moving the files would be a bigger change
and would break `scripts/generate-types.sh` and `check-contract-sync.sh`.\n\nWai
t, let me look at this from another angle. The PR is for "V1 Infrastructure Boot
strap". The mobile app currently doesn\'t use the generated models. Maybe the fi
x is simpler: just make the generated code valid so `flutter analyze` passes.\n\
nFor the `dart-dio` generated code with `built_value`, the standard workflow is:
\n1. Generate the code\n2. Run `build_runner` to generate `.g.dart` files\n3. Us
e the generated package as a dependency\n\nSince I can\'t run `build_runner`, ma
ybe I should:\n1. Add the path dependency to `pubspec.yaml`\n2. Update `scripts/
generate-types.sh` to run `flutter pub get` and `dart run build_runner build` in
the generated package\n3. Update `scripts/check-contract-sync.sh` to do the same
in the temp dir\n4. Remove the generated test files (which reference the package
) or keep them\n\nBut I still can\'t generate the `.g.dart` files to commit them
now. The CI would regenerate them if the script is updated... but the CI `design
-check` just runs `flutter analyze`, it doesn\'t run `make generate-types` first
.\n\nWait, let me look at the CI workflow again. The `design-check` job does:\n`
``yaml\n- name: Get Flutter packages\n  run: |\n    cd apps/mobile && flutter pu
b get\n    cd ../../packages/design-system && flutter pub get\n\n- name: Analyze
Flutter\n  run: |\n    cd apps/mobile && flutter analyze\n    cd ../../packages/
design-system && flutter analyze\n```\n\nIt doesn\'t run `make generate-types`. 
So if the `.g.dart` files are missing from the repo, they won\'t exist during CI
either.\n\nSo I need a fix that either:\na. Generates the `.g.dart` files as par
t of the repo\nb. Changes the CI to generate them before analyzing\nc. Changes t
he generator to not need `.g.dart` files\nd. Excludes the generated code from an
alysis\n\nOption (d) seems interesting. Can I add an `analysis_options.yaml` to 
`apps/mobile/` that excludes `lib/models/generated/**` from analysis? Let me che
ck if the mobile app already has one.',
